# Git & GitHub Commands Notes

## ‚ö° Most Used Commands

- **`git status`**  
  Displays the state of the working directory and staging area.
  - `-s` : Give the output in the short-format.

- **`git add .`**  
  Stages changes for the next commit.
  - `-A` or `--all` : Stages all changes (new, modified, and deleted files).
  - `-p` : Interactively stages changes (patch mode).

- **`git commit -m "msg"`**  
  Commits the staged snapshot.
  - `-m "msg"` : Sets the commit message.
  - `-a` : Automatically stages modified and deleted files (but not new/untracked ones) before committing.
  - `--amend` : Redoes the last commit (useful for fixing typos or adding forgotten files).

- **`git push`**  
  Uploads local content to a remote repo.
  - `-u origin <branch>` : Sets the upstream tracking reference.
  - `-f` or `--force` : Forces the push (overwrites remote history - dangerous!).
  - `--tags` : Pushes all tags to the remote.

- **`git pull`**  
  Fetches and merges changes from remote.
  - `--rebase` : Reapplies your local commits on top of the incoming changes (cleaner history).

- **`git clone <url>`**  
  Copies a remote repository.
  - `--depth 1` : Create a shallow clone with a history truncated to the latest commit (saves download size).

- **`git branch`**  
  Lists, creates, or deletes branches.
  - `-d <branch>` : Deletes the branch (safe delete).
  - `-D <branch>` : Force deletes the branch (ignores unmerged changes).
  - `-a` : Lists all local and remote branches.
  - `-m <old> <new>` : Renames a branch.

- **`git checkout <branch>`**  
  Switches branches or restores files.
  - `-b <new-branch>` : Creates and switches to a new branch.

- **`git merge <branch>`**  
  Joins history from another branch.
  - `--abort` : Aborts the merge and restores the pre-merge state (useful during conflicts).
  - `--no-ff` : Creates a merge commit even when a fast-forward is possible.

- **`git log`**  
  Shows commit history.
  - `--oneline` : Shows each commit as a single line (hash + message).
  - `--graph` : Draws a text-based graphical representation of the branches and merge history.
  - `-n <number>` : Limits the output to the last `<number>` commits.
  - `--stat` : Shows which files were altered.

---

## üõ†Ô∏è Setup & Configuration

- **`git config`**
  - `--global` : Applies configuration to the current user (all repos).
  - `--list` : Lists all Git settings.

- **`git init`**
  Initializes a new Git repository.

## üîÑ Undoing Changes

- **`git reset`**
  - `--soft <commit>` : Moves HEAD to `<commit>`, but leaves changes staged (ready to commit).
  - `--mixed <commit>` : (Default) Moves HEAD to `<commit>`, un-stages changes, but keeps them in working directory.
  - `--hard <commit>` : Moves HEAD to `<commit>` and destroys all changes.

- **`git restore <file>`**
  - `--staged` : Unstages the file (similar to `git reset HEAD <file>`).

- **`git clean`**
  Removes untracked files from the working tree.
  - `-n` : Dry run (shows what *would* be deleted).
  - `-f` : Force delete.
  - `-d` : Remove untracked directories as well.

## üì¶ Stashing

- **`git stash`**
  - `save "message"` : Stash with a descriptive message.
  - `pop` : Apply stash and remove from list.
  - `apply` : Apply stash but keep in list.
  - `list` : Show all stashes.
  - `drop` : Remove a specific stash.

## üîç Inspection & Comparison

- **`git diff`**
  - `--staged` (or `--cached`) : Shows changes in staging area vs last commit.
  - `--name-only` : Shows only names of changed files.
